ext4_fread: zero-fill holes in the aligned and tail paths.

Upstream ext4_fread() only guards holes (fblock==0) on the HEAD partial-
block path (if fblock != 0 ... else memset). The aligned/full-block loop
and the tail partial-block path both feed a hole's fblock straight into a
read, returning stale on-disk bytes (the partition's superblock area)
instead of zeros. Two fixes:

  1. Aligned loop: `fblock_start == 0` was used as a "run not started"
     sentinel, but 0 is a valid HOLE block; a hole followed by real data
     let the next block overwrite fblock_start and steal its data. Key the
     start-of-run off the run length instead, so a leading hole keeps
     fblock_start=0.
  2. Tail path: add the same `if (fblock != 0) ... else memset` guard the
     head path already has.

Surfaced as garbage pixels in games loading sparse assets (OMF 2097).
--- a/src/ext4.c	2026-07-17 22:57:47.354331210 -0700
+++ b/src/ext4.c	2026-07-17 22:57:47.356218681 -0700
@@ -1780,7 +1780,10 @@
 
 			iblock_idx++;
 
-			if (!fblock_start)
+			/* fblock 0 is a valid HOLE, not "unset": key the
+			 * start-of-run off the run length (never 0 after the
+			 * first block) so a leading hole keeps fblock_start=0. */
+			if (!fblock_count)
 				fblock_start = fblock;
 
 			if ((fblock_start + fblock_count) != fblock)
@@ -1811,10 +1814,16 @@
 		if (r != EOK)
 			goto Finish;
 
-		off = fblock * block_size;
-		r = ext4_block_readbytes(file->mp->fs.bdev, off, u8_buf, size);
-		if (r != EOK)
-			goto Finish;
+		/* fblock 0 is a HOLE: zero-fill like the head path
+		 * above (upstream omits this guard on the tail). */
+		if (fblock != 0) {
+			off = fblock * block_size;
+			r = ext4_block_readbytes(file->mp->fs.bdev, off, u8_buf, size);
+			if (r != EOK)
+				goto Finish;
+		} else {
+			memset(u8_buf, 0, size);
+		}
 
 		file->fpos += size;
 
